  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">It is worth noting that the present approach for the calculation of the lifetime τ of the black-hole n th mass (energy) level is based on the Bohr correspondence principle [4]. This approach is known to perform well in other areas of physics [34,35]. In particular, it is well known that, using the correspondence principle, the radiative lifetimes of hydrogenic atoms can be calculated, with a very high degree of accuracy, using the classical laws of radiation [34,35]. Moreover, it is known [34,35] that the agreement between the exact ( quantum -mechanically calculated) atomic lifetimes and the approximated ( classically calculated) lifetimes improves as the energy level n increases. (In fact, the quantum/classical agreement becomes perfect in the <math altimg="si56.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy="false">→</mo><mo>∞</mo></math> limit.) We expect a similar agreement to hold true in the physics of large [that is, <math altimg="si57.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>n</mi><mo>≫</mo><mn>1</mn></math> in Eq. (1)] black holes</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">33</subfield>
  </datafield>
