    <subfield code="y">2005</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">35</subfield>
    <subfield code="s">Phys.Rev.,A71,020501(R)</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Here we have used the relation <math altimg="si58.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>τ</mi><mo>≡</mo><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>d</mi><mi>N</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math> for the mean time between quantum leaps</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">36</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="h">Here J</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">is the angular momentum of the Kerr black hole</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">37</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Here we have used the area-entropy relation <math altimg="si59.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">BH</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>ħ</mi></math> for black holes</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">38</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Note that only positive frequency <math altimg="si60.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>ω</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math> modes (that is, field quanta with positive energy as measured by asymptotic observers) can be emitted by the black hole (that is, can reach infinity). Thus, the allowed values of the discrete parameters <math altimg="si61.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="false">{</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy="false">}</mo></math> are restricted by the requirement <math altimg="si62.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><msub><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">BH</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mi>ħ</mi><mo>⋅</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>m</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">H</mi></mrow></msub><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math></subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">39</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">We are interested in rapidly-rotating Kerr black holes with <math altimg="si63.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>O</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math>. These black holes are characterized by the relation [see Eq. (7)] <math altimg="si64.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">BH</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mi>ħ</mi><mo>≪</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">H</mi></mrow></msub></math>. Note that this strong inequality implies [see Eq. (10)] <math altimg="si65.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo>≪</mo><msub><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub></math> (and, in particular, <math altimg="si66.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mo>≪</mo><msub><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math> in the regime <math altimg="si67.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>k</mi><mo>⋅</mo><msub><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">BH</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mi>ħ</mi><mo>≪</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">H</mi></mrow></msub></math> ) for these rapidly-rotating Kerr black holes</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">40</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">It is worth noting that there is one important difference between our approach for the calculation of the Kerr black-hole emission rate and the closely related approach used in [6] for the calculation of the Schwarzschild black-hole emission rate. In [6] the authors modeled the radiating black hole as a perfect black-body emitter and used the Stefan-Boltzmann law in order to approximate the true radiation power of the Schwarzschild black hole. Below we shall consider the actual emission rates of Kerr black holes by properly taking into account the frequency-dependent grey-body factors [see Eq. (12) below] which quantify the partial scattering of the emitted field quanta by the effective curvature potential of the black-hole spacetime</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">41</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">As emphasized earlier [39], only positive frequency (energy) modes (as measured by asymptotic observers) can be emitted by the black hole [1,32]. Thus, the integral in (12) is restricted to the regime <math altimg="si60.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>ω</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math> [1,32]</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">42</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">In particular, one finds [32] that, for rapidly-rotating black holes, the semi-classical emission spectra are dominated by the gravitational ( <math altimg="si49.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>s</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math> ) field quanta with <math altimg="si68.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>s</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">43</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Note that the exponential factor that appears in the denominator of (12) implies that, for a given value of ω, the emission of modes with <math altimg="si69.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>m</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">H</mi></mrow></msub><mo></subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">44</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Here we take <math altimg="si74.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>γ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math> in the expression (11) for Δ ω. This order of magnitude is consistent with the most commonly used values of the dimensionless parameter γ, see [3,6-8]</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">45</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">We assume that the emitting black hole is large enough (that is, cold enough [see Eq. (7)]), such that the emission of massive particles of masses <math altimg="si75.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>M</mi><mi>μ</mi><mo>≫</mo><mi>ħ</mi></math> is exponentially suppressed [32]. [Note that in order to reach spatial infinity (that is, in order to be in an unbound state), the energy of emitted massive quanta should be characterized by the inequality <math altimg="si76.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>ħ</mi><mi>ω</mi><mo>≥</mo><mi>μ</mi></math>. Taking cognizance of Eqs. (12) and (14), one finds that the emission of such quanta (that is, massive quanta in the regime <math altimg="si77.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>ħ</mi><mi>ω</mi><mo>≥</mo><mi>μ</mi><mo>≫</mo><mi>ħ</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mi>M</mi></math> ) is exponentially suppressed.] It is worth emphasizing that extending the family of the emitted particles (for example, taking into account the emission of massive neutrinos from the black hole) would decrease the lifetime τ of the black-hole meta-stable state, and thus would increase the natural broadening δω of the black-hole emission lines [see Eq. (16)]. This effect would merely support our final conclusion [see Eq. (17) below] that the emission lines of rapidly-rotating Kerr black holes are effectively blended together</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">46</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Note that the exact value of <math altimg="si41.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">¯</mo></mrow></mover></math> at which <math altimg="si78.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>δ</mi><mi>ω</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi><mi>ω</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math> depends on the chosen value [3,6-8] of the dimensionless parameter γ</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">47</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">In fact, from (11) one finds the asymptotic relation <math altimg="si79.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>ζ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">¯</mo></mrow></mover><mo stretchy="false">→</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">→</mo><mo>∞</mo></math>. Note that this asymptotic behavior is independent of the value of the dimensionless parameter γ</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">48</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">It is worth emphasizing that by we mean a theory in which the black hole itself is properly quantized. This should be contrasted with the semi-classical analysis of Hawking [1], in which the matter fields are properly analyzed at the quantum level, but the black-hole spacetime itself is treated as a classical background</subfield>
    <subfield code="t">a quantum theory of gravity</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">49</subfield>
  </datafield>
